title: Grateful Dead Live at Campus Stadium, UC Santa Barbara on 1974-05-25
description:
Set 1

U.S. Blues, Mexicali Blues, Deal, Jack Straw, Scarlet Begonias, Beat It On Down The Line, Brown Eyed Women, Me & My Uncle, Sugaree, El Paso, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Around & Around

Set 2

Promised Land, Ship of Fools, Big River, Tennessee Jed, Truckin'-> Let It Grow-> Wharf Rat-> Beer Barrel Polka-> Sugar Magnolia-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> One More Saturday Night, E: Casey Jones

Other artist(s): Maria Muldar, Great American String Band, Elvin Bishop

reviews.review_text: buried deck gets automatic 10 stars All us deadheads laughin' all the way and this wall o' sound aud takes the cake. This show set list wise doesn't win the sweepstakes, but this recording along with the story makes me remember all the awesome nonbestever's I attended.

Another little nugget I just noticed... ... is the noise of a small, single-engine plane flying over the concert field, for about twenty seconds at the 6:30 mark in Sugaree!  By this time, the song is over and the sounds of the plane can easily be heard!

This is why I love good audience recordings~

Love this show While in the process of downloading my cassette collection to iTunes, I'm zapping this one now and I must say, what a treat.  Sounds fantastic blasting out of my bose dock system off iPod.  The energy is crazy good Jerry's playing rip and fast furious on Jackstraw and Mexicali.  My tapes are going up for display as I digitize my world for 2011 and beyond iPods and all.  Thank you for taping this, uploading and thank you archive.org.  As Phil says at the end of Jackstraw, "Thank YOU!"  The best organization next to The Dead.  This show is a must have!  Shake it!

GREAT FOB! Super cool FOB recording of the WALL OF SOUND. Well preserved and rich sounding...lots of bottom end. The high end is a little muddy, but who cares....this is one of the better recodings of the Wall of Sound on the Archive. Also, check out Rob Bertando's Hollywood Bowl recording from 7-21-1974, another benchmark recording of the WALL.

Great story about burying the tape deck to aviod getting busted carrying it in....very creative.
Great Show, Recording and Story Great recording of a very unique show. Alot of intensity here, one of my favorites.

Yep I arrived in LA in May of 74 and this was my 1st California show.  Interesting how the recording picks up the cross phasing issues they were having that day. They had yet to put up the true wall of sound that they had in July at the Hollywood Bowl. I remember a lot of sunburn and colorful Brannif jets taking off next to the stadium. Thanks for the memories.

midday at the oasis Down the road from marin Sunny fun in isla vista. What Yall don't remember a top left speaker falling 30ft to ground...collective acid ohhh. ahhh..no problem...it went thump in the grass yay .No one hurt. And the band played on. Yes it was a good show. Thanx archive. Tonk.

Amazing This is an incredible document of the Wall of Sound experience.  The recording of the bass is righteous.

All of this show is great but the standouts for me are the blazingly fast and tight (and short) version of Scarlet Begonias (great vocals by Donna - she gives Jerry a fine launching pad), an amazing and intense Let it Grow directly out of space (no Weather Report Suite intro) followed by a Wharf Rat that goes into a beautiful Dark Star jam (Keith!!!) and then into something that sounds a lot like Cryptical Envelopment. There's an unfortunate edit in this recording toward the end of the Wharf Rat but hang with it because Jerry isn't finished exploding your mind just yet.

I might have just left the show after the WRS->Wharf Rat because it's pretty impossible to top that.

My First Show! This show was my first, and it turned me from a "listener" into a Deadhead for Life.  I was a freshman at UCSB and had been introduced to the Grateful Dead the year before - I enjoyed the music, but it wasn't until seeing them live that I "got it".  The Wall of Sound was incredible, it was a beautiful Santa Barbara day, and the band was on fire! (And so was I, as I recall!!)  I saw the band many times since, as well as the Dead, Further and most of the members' peripheral bands, but I still enjoy listening to this show - truly a life-changing day for this gal!

Concert Set-up Was this an all day event with the Dead going on at night or a daytime performance?

What time did they wrap up?  TIA

Filmed it I brought in a 8mm projector. Shot regular 8 film, no sound. Got some great clips of the WALL. On YouTube search for "Grateful Dead: Live at the Campus Stadium, UC Santa Barbara on 1974-05-25 (no sound)". Link: https://youtu.be/HYt8RQQoMj     A Great day of music! I filmed the 2 openers too (GASB and Maria. Elvin did not perform that day).

Read Taper Notes Just the sheer amount of effort that went into Recording this show should give this AUD 5 stars. Great story and an incredible persistence for Dead music. I’m grateful. 

Also the show is pretty sick, they’re very fat here and keep blazing through the tracks. Overall this “sounds” like an old recording. Which I listen to only AUDs and usually I can find ones that sound pretty darn crisp for the time. But even with that said, the quality is charming and enjoyable without any difficulty at all.
